04429nam a22005295i 9780774851077DE-B159720240306124542.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||240306t20072004xxc    fo  d z      eng d  a97807748510777 a10.59962/97807748510772doi  a(DE-B1597)661763  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  axxccCA 4aE99.K9 ǂb A453 2004eb 7aSOC0210002bisacsh04a971.1004/97953/009200aPaddling to Where I Stand :bAgnes Alfred, Qwiqwasutinuxw Noblewoman /ced. by Martine J. Reid, Daisy Sewid-Smith. 1aVancouver ;aToronto : bUniversity of British Columbia Press, c[2007] 4c©2004  a1 online resource (325 p.) :b36 b&w photos, 8 illustrations, 1 map  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFront Matter -- tContents -- tPreface -- tAcknowledgments -- tIntroduction -- tMyth Time -- tWar, Conflict, and Slavery -- tChildhood -- tBecoming a Woman -- tMarrying Moses Alfred -- tCeremonies and Rituals -- tFragments of Recollections -- tEulogy for Granny?Axuẃ -- tEpilogue -- tLinguistic Key to the Kʷaќʷala Alphabet, Spelling, and Pronunciation¹ -- tMyth 9 – The Animal Kingdom -- tProhibition of the Potlatch¹ -- tTraditional Kʷakʷakeẃakʷ Wedding between Daisy Sewid (Qʷiqʷasutinuxʷ: Gilford Island) and Lorne Smith (λawicis: Turnour Island) -- tKinship Diagrams -- tNotes -- tReferences -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThe Kwakwakawakw people and their culture have been the subject of more anthropological writings than any other ethnic group on the Northwest Coast. Until now, however, no biography had been written by or about a Kwakwakawakw woman. Paddling to Where I Stand presents the memoirs of Agnes Alfred (c.1890-1992), a non-literate noble Qwiqwasutinuxw woman of the Kwakwakawakw Nation and one of the last great storytellers among her peers in the classic oral tradition. Agnes Alfred documents through myths, historical accounts, and personal reminiscences the foundations and the enduring pulse of her living culture. She shows how a First Nations woman managed to quietly fulfill her role as a noble matriarch in her ever-changing society, thus providing a role model for those who came after her. She also contributes significant light and understanding to several traditional practices including prearranged marriages and traditional potlatches. Paddling to Where I Stand is more than another anthropological interpretation of Kwakwaka'wakw culture. It is the first-hand account, by a woman, of the greatest period of change she and her people experienced since first contact with Europeans, and her memoirs flow from her urgently felt desire to pass on her knowledge to younger generations.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Ethnic Studies / Native American Studies.2bisacsh1 aReid, Martine J., eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aSewid-Smith, Daisy, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertACUP Complete eBook-Package Pre-2010z978311127416408iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertACUP Upgrade eBook-Package pre 2010z978311127724008iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of British Columbia eBook-Package 2013-2000z978311141860540uhttps://doi.org/10.59962/978077485107740uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780774851077423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780774851077/original  a978-3-11-127416-4  ACUP Complete eBook-Package Pre-2010b2010  a978-3-11-127724-0  ACUP Upgrade eBook-Package pre 2010b2010  a978-3-11-141860-5  University of British Columbia eBook-Package 2013-2000c2013d2000  aGBV-deGruyter-alles